  <mainDescription>&lt;h3 style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot;>&#xD;
    1 Introduction&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Developing adaptive software systems is a highly complex task.&#xD;
    This domain is by outset less understood and requires the users not only consider a single static system; rather, they&#xD;
    have to acquire a deep insight into the systemâ€™s context situations and how a plethora of system configurations can be&#xD;
    derived from these. Understanding the emergent behaviour of these types of systems is even more&#xD;
    challenging.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>In addition to the existing challenges of software&#xD;
    engineering, adaptive systems as a group involve additional tasks to specify the alternative paths a system can take in&#xD;
    selecting its configuration of functions and components, as well as the logic that decides which paths the system&#xD;
    should choose at any certain time depending on its context situation. Both of these tasks present their own set of&#xD;
    challenges, in particular when it comes to scaling; as the number of alternative paths of a system grows the set of&#xD;
    possible system configurations grows exponentially. Within the domain of adaptive systems, this is often referred to as&#xD;
    the problem of exponential growth (elaborated in&lt;/span> &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>[1]&lt;/span>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>). Firstly, we&#xD;
    require ways of designing and managing this growth of alternative paths, as traditional methods are not designed with&#xD;
    this in mind. Secondly, we require capturing the adaptation logic of the system in a way that abstracts the complexity&#xD;
    of exponential growth, both for developers at design-time and for the machines at runtime.&lt;/span>&lt;/font>&lt;/font>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>&lt;font size=&quot;3&quot; face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>DiVA proposes a model-driven approach using aspect-oriented&#xD;
    techniques to face these challenges. The project has thus fully embraced the Model-Driven Engineering (MDE) paradigm&#xD;
    and uses models as the first class entity during the entire software lifecycle; from development to runtime and&#xD;
    maintenance. &lt;span style=&quot;mso-spacerun: yes&quot;>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span>The details on these techniques are found in work packages&#xD;
    1-4, covering topics such as requirements engineering, modelling of adaptive systems, using models at runtime to drive&#xD;
    adaptation, and design- and runtime reasoning. However, the potential value of these techniques is not reached unless&#xD;
    there is a framework that ties them all together and shows the developer a complete and consistent approach on how to&#xD;
    develop adaptive systems. This is the role of the DiVA methodology; to provide a guideline and a set of best practices&#xD;
    on how to use the full force of the technologies developed in DiVA to develop adaptive systems. As such, the&#xD;
    methodology can be considered the link that presents the state-of-the-art technology in a way that the developers can&#xD;
    use.&lt;/font>&lt;/span>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>This deliverable is organised as follows. Section&lt;/span>&#xD;
    &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>2&lt;/span> &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>presents an overview of the DiVA methodology, presenting the scope,&#xD;
    design principles and structure of the methodology. Section&lt;/span> &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>3&lt;/span> &lt;span&#xD;
    lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>outlines the case study used throughout the methodology to illustrate the process. Finally,&#xD;
    Sections&lt;/span> &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>4&lt;/span>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>-&lt;/span>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>7&lt;/span> &lt;span&#xD;
    lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>explains the four practicess that constitute the DiVA methodology.&lt;/span>&lt;/font>&lt;/font>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h4 style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot;>&#xD;
    1.1 &lt;a id=&quot;_Toc267555670&quot; name=&quot;_Toc267555670&quot;>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>Intended audience&lt;/span>&lt;/a>&#xD;
&lt;/h4>&#xD;
&lt;p style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 10pt&quot; class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;font size=&quot;3&quot;>&lt;font face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>The audience for this methodology is the developer of&#xD;
    adaptive systems. DiVA uses state-of-the-art research within model-driven engineering and adaptive systems, however,&#xD;
    including an introduction to these topics would require too much space and divert the reader from the goal of the&#xD;
    methodology. Consequently, the document assumes that the reader has basic familiarity with the concepts of model-driven&#xD;
    engineering, aspect-oriented development, and context-aware, adaptive systems. A brief overview of these results and&#xD;
    how they make up the DiVA approach is given in Section&lt;/span> &lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>2.2&lt;/span>&lt;span lang=&quot;EN-GB&quot;>, but the&#xD;
    reader is anyhow advised to read the deliverables explaining the technical tools and results that allow the development&#xD;
    and running of adaptive systems. This is meant as a background for understanding the methodology that is presented in&#xD;
    the following sections.&lt;/span>&lt;/font>&lt;/font>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
